Here's what's gonna happen when the Federal Reserve increases the interest rate
The interest rate will increase and the bull market (growth market) will be staggered, bond profitability will increase and the economy will enter into recession.
That's what we know.
What we don't know is how long it's going to happen and how long it's going to last.
In the economy, history offers few clues as to time frame.
After the first increase in interest rates, the recession took only 11 months and lasted 86 months.
The aggressiveness of the Federal Reserve to increase interest rates is often, although not always, a determining factor in how the economy and financial assets respond.
This is why US central bank officials have emphasized so strongly that investors should not focus on the moment when they start to increase the interest rate but on the trajectory of the time needed for normalisation.
Indeed, in the game are multiple variables.
In the end, however, market players may find that all the unrest associated with rising interest rates has been exaggerated.
"The first increase in the interest rate decided by the Fed after the global financial crisis will inevitably be interpreted by some voices as a sign of the "cheap money" era," said Julian Jessop, chief economist at Capital Economics, in a note addressed to customers.
On the contrary, we do not expect the gradual return of US interest rates to more normal levels but still to be the seismic shock that all seem to fear.
But it cannot be said that there will be no effects.
Here is how it could react to a few sectors of the economy, based on historical trends:
Given the situation faced by the market in recent months, anticipating the rise in the interest rate can volatilise things for a while.
But at the time of growth, the impact is not so dramatic.
"It seems that there is a tendency for capital profitability to stagnate for 12-24 months after the first increase, which may reflect the monetary policy gap again," Deutsche Bank analysts said in a recent study on what will happen after the Fed increases.
Specifically, over the past 35 years, the market has increased sharply - by about 14 percent - towards increasing the interest rate, quite unchanged over the 250 days after (average rise of 2.6%) after which it returns to normal after 500 days, with an average return in the last six cycles of 14.4%, according to a recent analysis published on Barron by the chief strategy of Nuveen Asset Management.
Deutsche stated that the impact on shares tends to become more pronounced later in the interest rate growth cycle and the benefits start to decline.
The recession is a reality of economic life but rising interest rates often contribute to it.
In the present situation, the Fed is facing conditions that have not existed before and that could accelerate a recession.
Specifically, the gross domestic product will approach its historical minimum point for an increase in Fed interest rate.
According to Deutsche Bank, of the 118 interest rate increases after 1950, only twice the nominal GDP was less than 4.5%.
Although in the second quarter of 2015 the value was 3.6%, few expect the situation to persist, the third quarter reaching only 1.5%, according to Atlanta Fed.
Increasing the interest rate in such a fragile economy could be risky and could raise the question "if this time is different," Deutsche said.
Market players have been preparing all year for an Fed growth decision, all eyes being focused on this week's meeting of the Federal Open Market Commission, which ends on Thursday.
While many policy-makers and economists believe that the FOMC could approve an increase in interest rate at this meeting, forward transactions indicate a probability of only 25%.
"In our post-1950 study, all interest rate growth cycles so far have been in a super profit growth cycle, with GDP evading peaks before the recession very quickly after the recovery began," the report said.
On the contrary, this was a strange slow recovery after the worst recession of the period under review.
The current cycle is by far the longest awaited by the Fed since the end of the last recession; the record had been 35 months, and it reached 74 months and continues.
Fixed income was also volatile as the market anticipates an increase in interest rate and the pattern is somewhat similar to that of dividends.
The main difference is that the impact is faster for bonds than for shares when the Fed changes policy.
In the case of bonds, it appears that the benefits change direction as soon as the first increase/decrease in the cycle occurs.
At the end of the interest rate growth cycle, the return on bonds drops immediately," Deutsche said.
The Charles Schwab strategy is of the opinion that these interest rate increases will bring about a closeness of profitability between short-term and long-term bonds, flattening the curve.
High-profit obligations do better in such an environment, although "we are still cautious about forcing profitability," Kathy Jones, a fixed-income analyst in Schwab, said in an analysis.
Interestingly, Jones is of the opinion that markets have already adapted to Fed policy expectations.
"Besides the dollar's power and the decrease in estimated inflation, there are a few signs that the market has adapted to the prospect of a more rigorous monetary policy," Jones wrote.
Short-term interest rates have increased, the yield curve is fairer, the spread of the average credit interest rate has expanded and volatility has increased - all market features when the Fed tightens policy.
Broadly speaking, companies operating in the US will gain from rising interest rates and local products will become more attractive.
Multinationals with large debts will suffer because the increase in the dollar will lead to the cost of their products in the global market space and their debt will be more expensive.
‘History shows that ‘quality' stocks tend to be more profitable in the three months following an initial increase in the interest rate', Goldman Sachs said in a customer report.
Firms with strong balance sheets outperformed those with a weak balance sheet after each of the interest rate increases in 1994, 1999 and 2004, with an average of 5 percentage points.
Companies with high capital and low volatility stocks also exceeded similar companies with a lower quality, with an average of 4 (percentage points) and 3 (percentage points) respectively.
Debt will become an important issue.
Companies with a high percentage of floating debt have the most to lose, Goldman says.
Consumers will also have to earn from the dollar increase.
Those who save could also have won, although experts do not agree on how quickly this will happen.
