The advantages and disadvantages of converting credits into Swiss francs
Two offers of conversion of credit into Swiss francs have already appeared on the banking market, the main advantages being the exclusion of currency risk and the reduction of rates.
Disadvantages can come in a few years, when variable interest can lead to higher rates.
Banca Transilvania has just concluded the process of conversion of loans into francs granted by Volksbank, and Bancpost announced the offer of conversion for its customers.
According to the cumulative data of FinZoom financial portal analysts, Bancpost offers three years of fixed interest on lei, of 1.5%, the smallest on the market.
On the other hand, the conversion offer of the Transylvanian bank was accepted by 83% of clients with credits in French due to the second successive reductions: the balance with the value of the risk and management commissions paid by the client was reduced, then an additional 22.5% reduction was applied to the balance in lei.
Both offers reduce the rates of their customers, compared to the monthly plateau equivalent in lei before conversion.
Thus, Banca Transilvania reduces the rate by 42.5% and Bancpost by 33% in the first three years and, theoretically, by 18% in the following years.
Benefits
The main advantage of the debt collection in the CHF is that the currency risk is eliminated, the consumer being protected from future increases in the franc, and the repayment of the credit will be made in the currency in which he cashes his salary.
Another major advantage of both conversion offers is that the property is not re-assessed, additional guarantees are no longer required and another proof of revenue is required.
In practice, there will be no new financial and legal analysis of the credit and no additional costs as in the case of a refinancing.
Also, both banks offer a discount at the monthly rate, compared to the amount of pre-conversion customers, equivalent in lei.
Risks
The problem is that the rate in the first years is more of the interest, and the customer pays back very little of the main.
The Bancpost offer with very small interest in the first three years seems advantageous to customers.
It is not known how this interest will evolve after three years.
The margin offered to customers can be more than 3.25%, so the total cost reduction is smaller.
A possible risk for all lei loans with variable interest is that the ROBOR index will grow significantly in the following years (more than the Libor index - CHF).
For example, three-month ROBOR is now 1.44%, but in 2013 it had reached 6%, in 2009 it was over 15%, and in a few days since 2008 it has exceeded 40%!
