On the occasion of the most expected meetings in recent years, policy makers in the Federal Reserve will spend two days this week around a 27-legged Mahon Honduran table to decide whether the time has come to increase a key interest rate for the first time in nearly a decade.
Above them, at the end of the central bank's meeting room, a mural of the United States will be unveiled.
The map is intended to recall that Janet L. Yellen, President of the Fed, and his colleagues must put the economic interests of the nation above all else.
The Central Bank has received a dual task from Congress: to maximise the employment rate in the US and to maintain price stability.
But since the great economic crisis, Fed leaders have confirmed that there is a third unwritten task: financial stability.
And this third task could be factor X in a decision too difficult to anticipate, which will be announced on Tuesday, and which will determine whether the US economy is prepared to be rid of the unprecedented incentive offered by the near-zero short-term interest rate in effect since the end of 2008.
Even if most data indicate a strong growing economy, recent turmoil in global financial markets could scare Fed officials already cautious about adding volatility by increasing the reference rate to federal funds - even with only a quarter of a percentage point.
"Obviously, the labour market and inflation will be the first and main aspects they will pursue," said Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economist at the brokerage firm Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
"However, I believe that if they were looking for an excuse not to increase the rate of interest, the growing uncertainty on the world market is enough to provide them with arguments to wait," she said.
There is no consensus as to which decision the Fed will take, which in itself leads to instability in the financial market.
About half of the recent Bloomberg-questioned economists anticipated an increase in interest rate this week.
But the financial markets expect the Fed to postpone, a key indicator showing that the probability of growth is only 30%.
This would indicate a drop on the stock exchange if Fed increased the interest rate, unless policymakers mitigated the blow by promising that it would pass a long time until the next increase.
On Tuesday, industrial average Dow Jones climbed 228.89 points, or 1.4%, to 16,599.85.
The advance was triggered by expectations that Fed decision makers will maintain stable interest rate this week, said John Lonski, chief economist at Moody's Capital Markets Research Group.
"It would be surprising for Fed to increase the interest rate at this time," Lonski said.
If the Fed decision-makers would do so, "they should act in depth in their policies to avoid panic in the financial markets".
Other experts said that an increase in the interest rate would calm the financial markets because it would remove the uncertainty about when the Fed would act.
Just a month ago, Fed seemed to be about to increase the rate by 0.25% this month, the first small step towards slow tightening monetary conditions that would confirm the strength of the US recovery.
Yellen said in the spring and early summer that he was expecting an increase in the interest rate this year despite the high objections of liberals like that he would need more economic progress.
Although job creation slowed down in August, labour market growth was solid this year.
The unemployment rate fell to 5.1% last month, the lowest percentage in more than seven years and close to the level considered by the Fed as total employment.
Wages showed signs of growth.
And while inflation continued to fail to meet the central bank's annual target, Fed decision makers claimed that a key reason was the temporary effect of sharply declining oil prices.
The economy "can cope with higher rates and needs them, given the pressure on the labour market," said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
But global financial markets began to enter fibrillations at the end of this month, after China devalued its currency.
Industrial average Dow Jones fell by 16% below the peak in May, as investors feared that the slowdown in the Chinese economy would bring down global growth.
The market has somewhat declined this month, with the Dow index now about 10% below the May maximum.
For Fed decision makers, market turmoil is added to the complex calculation of the interest rate growth time.
"Without what has happened on the financial markets and the news about the weakening of the Chinese economy in recent weeks, it would be firmer in the meeting," said Stephen D. Oliner, a researcher with experience at UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and former official Fed.
Now, he plans to wait at least a month to better manage the effects.
"There is a lot of uncertainty about what the impact will be on the U.S. economy and they almost have no data to rely on later events in China," Oliner said.
The welfare of the global economy is not one of the main interests of the Fed, so it should not be taken into account in decision-making.
But in reality, the Fed has become the world's monetary authority.
In recent years, the influence of the central bank has been huge.
The President's simple allusion since then, Ben S. Bernanke, in 2013, that the Fed could "long" its monetary expansion triggered an earthquake on world markets.
In a world where markets and economies are becoming more and more entangled, Fed officials are expected not only to monitor progress in other areas, but also to consult with other central banks and experts to better interpret the world economy.
Its decision-making process is "more art than science," said Zachary Karabell, head of the Global Strategy Department at the Envestnet Welfare Management Inc.
Jeffrey Lacker, President Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond, Va., said this month that "Fed has an oversized reaction history to changes in the financial market that seem unrelated to economic bases."
Lacker, a voting member of the Federal Commission for the Open Market, a decision-making body that supported the rise in the interest rate, offered as an example the decisions of 1998-99.
A financial crisis that affected Asia led Fed to reduce the reference rate by 0.75% in three meetings, "despite the implications of limited identification for US development," Lacker said.
A year later, the Fed officials returned to those falls.
The Fed should put the issue of financial stability first only in the event of a major crisis, such as the 2008 market earthquake, said Adam S. Posen, a former member of the Bank of England interest rate commission.
The last turbulent period does not rise to that level, he said.
"We certainly don't want to get into the situation of fearing an increase in the interest rate because markets have been upset," said Posen, President Peterson Institute for International Economics.
The Federal Reserve Act continues to have a dual mandate and does not mention financial stability, and until something changes in this regard, I do not think that we should take premature action.
