Weight reduction surgery could be useful for diabetics with mild obesity
The benefits of weight reduction surgery for people with mild obesity with type 2 diabetes could be maintained for at least five years, according to a new study.
It is still premature to tell whether diabetics with mild obesity live longer after weight loss surgery than those who undergo non-surgical treatments.
"It takes a long time to centralize mortality data," said Dr. Robin Blackstone, a specialist in obesity surgery, as she wrote an article about the new study in JAMA Surgery.
Operations for weight loss, also called bariatric surgery, use various methods to lower your stomach.
They reduce the feeling of hunger and limit the body's ability to absorb food.
Over the years, bariatric surgery has been effective in treating type 2 diabetes, but most studies have been conducted in people with morbid obesity, with a body mass index (BMI) 35 or higher.
BMI, a height-weight unit, is considered normal in the 18.5-24.9 range.
The BMI of at least 25 indicates that one person is overweight and people with BMI over 30 are considered obese.
You can calculate your BMI by accessing: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For the new study, researchers at Min-Sheng General Hospital in Taiwan used the data collected after 2007 in a trial comparing two types of bariatric surgery - gastric bypass and gastrectomy in the cuff - in the medical treatment of type 2 diabetes mellitus in people with mild obesity.
Mean BMI in those undergoing surgery decreased from 31 to 24.5 to the end of the fifth year in the study.
In the meantime, BMI in people who have received non-surgical diabetes treatments remained close to the same level, i.e. 29.
Of those who had surgery, diabetes was completely cured at 36% and partially at 28%.
In the group treated by medical methods, by comparison, diabetes mellitus was completely cured to only 1% and partially to only 2% of subjects.
In addition, blood pressure control, triglycerides and "bad" LDL cholesterol "have generally been better in the surgical group", the authors concluded.
Researchers also monitored the blood level of haemoglobin A1c, which reflects the level of blood glucose over time.
Researchers write that the optimal level of haemoglobin A1c is below 7%.
After surgery, the mean haemoglobin level of A1c decreased from approximately 9% to approximately 6%.
However, in the group treated by medical methods, it remained at about 8%.
However, this improved "glycaemic control" - reflected in improved haemoglobin A1c levels - did not reduce the mortality rate to five years, according to Chief Researcher Dr. Chih-Cheng Hsu and colleagues.
The research team also compared the average results associated with the two types of surgery.
In the fifth year, compared to the gastrectomy group in the cuff, the bypass surgery group lost more weight (18.7 versus 14.2 kg), experienced a greater decrease in BMI (7.4 versus 5.1) and haemoglobin A1c (3.1% versus 2.1%) and presented a higher probability of complete remission of diabetes (46.9% versus 16.7%).
Although the new study does not indicate a benefit in survival or surgery after five years, there is evidence from a study conducted on people with high weight in Sweden that surgery prolongs the life, says Blackstone, from Arizona University, Faculty of Medicine - Phoenix.
In the Swedish study, obese individuals who underwent bariatric surgery were approximately 29% less likely to die after 15 years than a group who tried more conventional methods.
Although the new study did not indicate a survival benefit in patients undergoing surgery, Blackstone stated that it is an optimistic aspect for individuals with BMI below 35 procedural stakeholders.
"This is the point where this work is critical because it states that this surgery is safe in the lower BMI group", without increasing the risk of death or kidney disease, she says.
Blackstone added that patients and their doctors should start taking weight seriously then the patient's BMI reaches 27-30.
"I think we wait too long to urge people to take this aspect seriously," she said.
I think once they've accumulated these genetic changes that short-circuited their bodies by predisposing them to obesity and diabetes, it's extremely hard to get back to normal.
