Four-fold increase in the number of children who have ingested hand detergent in the last 4 years
According to the Georgia Anti-Oil Center, the U.S. Anti-Oil Centers reported an increase of approximately 400% since 2010 in the number of children under the age of 12 who swallowed high-alcohol hand detergent.
According to Dr. Gaylord Lopez, the director of the Georgia Poisoning Centre, cases of ingestion of hand detergent in children under the age of 12 reported at the anti-poisoning centres rose from 3,266 in 2010 to 16,117 in 2014.
"Children have more frequent access to these products and, unfortunately, a percentage of them reach the emergency room," Lopez told CNN.
Lopez said that some children drink detergent intentionally and others do it to impress their friends or to respond to challenges on social networks.
On YouTube can be watched movies that present teens as they drink detergent to create cheap drinks.
It seems that teenagers have mixed the detergent with alcohol to get a stronger drink.
Younger children may be attracted by the attractive smell of detergent.
"A child doesn't think he's hurting him," Lopez says.
Many of the most attractive types (hand detergent) are perfumed ones.
Hand detergents with strawberry flavor, grape, orange are the most attractive for children.
The hand detergent contains approximately 45-95% alcohol.
Especially in young children, only a few swallows can cause alcohol poisoning.
"It's very concentrated alcohol," said Dr. Stephen Thornton, Medical Director of the Anti-Poison Center at Kansas University Hospital, for Channel Fox 4 in Kansas City.
Thus, we avoid leaving a glass of whiskey on the table, but people leave these hand detergents in accessible places and if the little ones get to them, this is a quick way to consume a lot of alcohol.
Nhaijah Russell, a six-year-old girl who recently ingested at school the equivalent of four hand detergent sprays with strawberry flavor, reached the emergency room to receive treatment.
He had alcoholemia179, twice as much as the threshold at which an adult is considered by law under the influence of alcohol, according to Dr. Chris Ritchey, a doctor in the emergency room who treated her at the Gwinnett Medical Center outside Atlanta.
Nhaijah was babbling and couldn't go when he got to the emergency room.
Doctors monitored her overnight in a separate children's hospital to identify signs of brain damage because the girl fell and hit her head because of the alcohol, Ritchey said.
"It was scary," Ortoria Scott, Nhaijah's mother, told CNN.
It could have been fatal to them.
Lopez advised parents and teachers to use products or wet towels without alcohol and to stop leaving hand detergent in the hands of children.
In addition to alcohol poisoning, some detergents have been associated with deaths.
In 2013, two women in Ontario died after swallowing hand detergent containing an unreported toxic ingredient.
Sanitary authorities assumed that the product contained methanol, a lethal substance, and not alcohol, specified as an active ingredient.
In January, three fourth - grade students in northern New York plotted to poison their "bad" teacher by "putting antibacterial products in class," according to a police report.
The teacher is very allergic to hand detergent and banned it in her classroom.
The police considered the plan to be "insignificant" and raised the disciplinary issue with the school inspectorate.
