FriendsFest: The comedy series that taught us important lessons about friendship among men
The absence of similar characters in the series is evident, since the need for men to open is now more desperate than ever, with suicide rates among young men reaching the top of the last 15 years.
In 2013, suicide was the leading cause of death in men aged 20-45 in the UK, and remains three times more common in men than in women.
In an attempt to address the issue, the Campaign Against Unhappy Life (CALM) designated 2015 as the Year of Man, wanting to question the culture that prevents men from seeking help when they need it.
Friendship lies at the heart of the struggle for the success of this challenge.
A recent study of more than 2000 high school students with symptoms of depression concluded that if the patient is surrounded by enough friends "with a healthy mood", his chances of recovery are doubled.
To the same extent, for people who are not depressed, a circle of healthy mental friends reduces the likelihood of mental disorders to half.
Of course, for friendship to work, it must first be accessible.
In this age of communication dominated by social networks, where emphasis is placed on style rather than substance, the immediate nature of the response often has priority before contact with meaning.
Our digital lives have doubled the need to create the appearance of a powerful personality, open to fun and success, even if in reality isolation is the one that dominates.
This superficial success is dominated by what psychologists call extrinsic values; money, image, social status, all at the cost of intrinsic values - our inner desire for personal development and friendship - which further affects our mental health.
The billionaire inventor of a video game recently explained that money really doesn't buy happiness.
The beauty of the Friends series was that it focused on this idea.
Characters were not defined by work but by their own personality, which they showed by interacting as friends.
The humor of Joey and Chandler's frequent hugs, the moments when he looks at football in the comfortable armchairs and Ross' passion for Rachel came from the fact that it is known that men can associate with this situation, even though they often fail to fully explore their feelings.
As one social worker explained to me: ..."My role in listening to people with suicidal and depressed tendencies has shown how even the smallest interactions with friends can make a difference."
Often, people who call on us don't feel able to talk to friends.
The old saying to deal with yourself is strong, as is the feeling of being perceived as a weak person if you speak openly about problems.
Friends is one of the series that comes to mind when I try to offer more mechanisms for long-term psychological adaptation.
The series highlighted the small moments of friendship between men.
As much as it helps the objective, external intervention, through the telephone, people arriving in moments of despair, long-term support comes from the family and close friends.
So, if you attend this weekend at FriendsFest organized by Comedy Central, with the complete recording of the film plates to celebrate the event, why not invite your friends to a coffee in Central Perk.
Or, even better, if you see someone alone in Starbucks, smile and say hello.
You never know what difference your friendship could make.
